Statement to verify:
The Spanish made landfall in Mexico in 1517. A Spanish settler in Cuba, Hernán Cortés, led an expedition (entrada) to Mexico, landing in February 1519, following an earlier expedition led by Juan de Grijalva to Yucatán in 1517. Two years later Cortés and his retinue set sail, thus beginning the expedition of exploration and conquest. The Spanish campaign against the Aztec Empire had its final victory on August 13, 1521, when a coalition army of Spanish forces and native Tlaxcalan warriors led by Cortés and Xicotencatl the Younger captured the Emperor Montezuma and Tenochtitlan, the capital of the Aztec Empire. The fall of Tenochtitlan marks the beginning of Spanish rule in Central Mexico, and they established their capital of Mexico City on the ruins of Tenochtitlan.

1. Who was the Spanish settler in Cuba who led the expedition to Mexico in 1519?
2. What was the outcome of the Spanish campaign against the Aztec Empire on August 13, 1521?
3. How did the establishment of Mexico City relate to the fall of Tenochtitlan in terms of Spanish rule in Central Mexico?
4. Can you provide the timeline of key events from the Spanish arrival in Mexico in 1517 to the establishment of Mexico City on the ruins of Tenochtitlan?
